{
  "texts": [
    "In this framework, the Mahalanobis distance is computed for the target building T 19, considering the difference for the weights of neural network representing the DRL control policy before and after fine-tuning in online TL and online DRL (with weights randomly initialised).",
    "The average Mahalanobis distance for the weights differences of all layers is lower for the online TL approach (i.e., 0.96) compared to the case of online DRL (i.e., 1.42), indicating that the weights distribution for online TL is more similar than the case of online DRL.",
    "Therefore, employing a lower learning rate ensures that the pre-existing knowledge from source building is not entirely discarded.",
    "To conclude, when the price schedule implemented in the target building follows an on-off peak pattern, the reward weight factor δ for the electricity cost term is doubled compared to that of the source agent for offline DRL, online DRL and OTL controllers.",
    "This adjustment is required to maintain a balance between the two terms in the reward function since TOU price tariff implemented in the source building features a higher average weekly electricity price compared to the on-off peak tariff."
  ]
}